{"episode_id":"82","task":"As of the 2020 census, what was the population difference between the largest county seat and smallest county seat, by land area of the county seat, in Washington state? For population figures, please use the official data from data.census.gov. Please report the integer difference.","domain":"Open World Tool QA","num_turns":24,"total_tokens":968692,"state":"success","trajectory":[{"turn_idx":0,"action":"file_saver({\"file_path\": \"work_space/gaia_d1af70ea_20251222_083432_425876/step0_scope_criteria_sources.md\", \"content\": \"Washington State County Seats Land-Area Extremes — Scope, Criteria, Sources, and Tie-Break Rules\\n\\nObjective\\n- Determine, as of the 2020 Census, the population difference between:\\n  1) The county seat in Washington state with the largest land area (by incorporated place/CDP land area per Census 2020 Gazetteer), and\\n  2) The county seat in Washington state with the smallest land area (same definition),\\n  using official 2020 population counts from data.census.gov (Decennial Census, P.L. 94-171, Table P1: Total population).\\n- Report the integer difference.\\n\\nScope and Definitions\\n- Geography: All 39 counties in Washington state and their official county seats.\\n- County seat definition: The primary county government seat designated by the county/state. Mapping will be to the corresponding Census “place” (incorporated city/town or CDP) that represents the county seat.\\n- Land area measure: 2020 Census Gazetteer Files for Places (state=Washington), field ALAND (land area in square meters). Water area (AWATER) is excluded by definition.\\n- Population measure: 2020 Decennial Census Redistricting Data (P.L. 94-171), Table P1, Total population, from data.census.gov, for the identified county seat place.\\n\\nPrimary Data Sources\\n- Land area (ALAND): 2020 Gazetteer Files — Places (Washington)\\n  • Source: U.S. Census Bureau 2020 Gazetteer (Places) by state\\n  • Fields: GEOID, NAME, ALAND (m^2), AWATER (m^2), etc.\\n- Population (2020): data.census.gov — Decennial Census, Redistricting Data (P.L. 94-171), Table P1: Total population, for each identified county seat place in WA.\\n- County seat roster (for mapping): An authoritative list of Washington county seats to be used for crosswalk to Census place names. Candidate sources include:\\n  • Washington Secretary of State: County officials directory / county seats\\n  • Washington State Association of Counties (WSAC): County seat information\\n  • Individual county websites (as needed for verification)\\n\\nTie-Break and Special Handling Rules\\n- Land-area extremes:\\n  • Largest seat by land area: select the place with maximum ALAND (2020 Gazetteer).\\n  • Smallest seat by land area: select the place with minimum ALAND (2020 Gazetteer).\\n- If multiple seats share the exact same maximum or minimum ALAND value, break ties alphabetically by Census place NAME (A–Z).\\n- If a county seat is an unincorporated community, use its Census-designated place (CDP) that matches the seat name. If no CDP exists, escalate for manual verification and document the approach; if needed, use the best Census place that represents the seat as listed by the state.\\n- Use 2020 boundaries and 2020 population counts to ensure temporal alignment.\\n- Units:\\n  • Land area: taken directly from ALAND (m^2). No unit conversion is required for ranking; any presented values may be annotated in km^2 or mi^2 if needed, but rankings will be based on ALAND.\\n  • Population: integer total from P.L. 94-171 Table P1.\\n\\nQuality Assurance and Validation\\n- Verify each county seat mapping to a unique Census place NAME and GEOID.\\n- Confirm that each county seat belongs to the correct county.\\n- Cross-check unusual/small area values to ensure no boundary anomalies or naming mismatches.\\n- For any ambiguous or renamed places, rely on 2020-era official names as used in Gazetteer and data.census.gov.\\n\\nPlanned Workflow\\n- Step 1: Compile and validate dataset\\n  • Assemble an authoritative list of WA county seats and map each to its Census place NAME and GEOID (2020).\\n  • Extract ALAND from the 2020 Gazetteer (Places) for Washington and join to the county seat crosswalk.\\n  • Validate name/ID alignment; resolve anomalies.\\n- Step 2: Identify extremes and retrieve populations\\n  • Determine the county seat with the largest and smallest ALAND.\\n  • Query data.census.gov for each seat’s 2020 total population (P.L. 94-171, Table P1) and record the values.\\n- Step 3: Compute and report\\n  • Compute the integer difference between the two populations.\\n  • Produce a concise, source-cited result per the output formatting requirements.\\n\\nDeliverable Formatting Rules\\n- Final answer will be an integer number only (no commas, currency symbols, or percent signs).\\n- Supporting notes will document selected seats, sources (with URLs/identifiers), ALAND figures, and P1 populations.\\n\\nNotes\\n- The explicit list of Washington county seats will be compiled and validated in Step 1 using authoritative sources before extraction and measurement.\\n\"})","observation":"Content successfully saved to work_space/gaia_d1af70ea_20251222_083432_425876/step0_scope_criteria_sources.md"},{"turn_idx":1,"action":"mark_step({\"step_index\": 0, \"step_status\": \"completed\", \"step_notes\": \"Defined scope, criteria, sources, and tie-break rules for identifying Washington’s largest and smallest county seats by land area (2020) and computing the 2020 population difference from data.census.gov. Saved document at: work_space/gaia_d1af70ea_20251222_083432_425876/step0_scope_criteria_sources.md\"})","observation":"Step 0: step_status is completed, step_notes is Defined scope, criteria, sources, and tie-break rules for identifying Washington’s largest and smallest county seats by land area (2020) and computing the 2020 population difference from data.census.gov. Saved document at: work_space/gaia_d1af70ea_20251222_083432_425876/step0_scope_criteria_sources.md "},{"turn_idx":2,"action":"tavily_search({\"query\": \"site:wikipedia.org List of counties in Washington county seat\"})","observation":"{'query': 'List of counties in Washington county seat', 'follow_up_questions': None, 'answer': None, 'images': [], 'results': [{'url': 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_counties_in_Washington', 'title': 'List of counties in Washington', 'content': '# List of counties in Washington. | Chelan County | 007 | Wenatchee | 1899 | Okanogan and Kittitas Counties | A Native American \"Native American (U.S.)\") word meaning \"deep water\", referring to Lake Chelan | 81,228 | 2,920\\xa0sq\\xa0mi (7,563\\xa0km2) |  |. | Stevens County | 065 | Colville | 1863 | Walla Walla County | Isaac Stevens (1818–1862), 1st Governor of the Washington Territory | 49,015 | 2,478\\xa0sq\\xa0mi (6,418\\xa0km2) |  |. | Thurston County | 067 | Olympia | 1852 | Lewis County | Samuel Thurston (1815–1851), the Oregon Territory\\'s first delegate to U.S. Congress | 302,912 | 722\\xa0sq\\xa0mi (1,870\\xa0km2) |  |. ## Former counties. 1. **^** \"Washington: Consolidated Chronology of State and County Boundaries\". ^ ***a*** ***b*** ***c*** \"Washington: Consolidated Chronology of State and County Boundaries\". \"The Naming of Counties in the State of Washington\". * Washington State Association of Counties. List of counties in Washington.', 'score': 0.9988213, 'raw_content': None}, {'url': 'https://simple.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_counties_in_Washington', 'title': 'List of counties in Washington', 'content': '| Adams County | 001 | Ritzville | 1883 | Whitman County | John Adams (1735–1826), 2nd U.S. President | 20,613 | 1,925\\xa0sq\\xa0mi (4,986\\xa0km2) |. | Lincoln County | 043 | Davenport | 1883 | Whitman County | Abraham Lincoln (1809–1865), 16th U.S. President | 10,876 | 2,311\\xa0sq\\xa0mi (5,985\\xa0km2) |. | Pierce County | 053 | Tacoma | 1852 | Thurston County | Franklin Pierce (1804–1869), 14th U.S. President | 921,13